And the wall came crashing down.
Here is a history quiz for history buffs: it was 20 years ago, in 1989, which was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4.
What do you remember most and which one had the most significant consequences for the planet ?
The Bloody Suppression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) Elections in Poland
Few are those who answer c).
Because the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, eclipsed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
However, nothing has contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and consequently to the post-war reordering of the international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism over the coming months, particularly the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people it was a moment of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But after having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern bloc from the outset, one realizes that the process has been long and complex.
The election in Poland was a point of no return, the moment when the movement in favour of change became irreversible.
He had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader heading Poland, General Jaruzelski, decided that the country's economic problems were too severe for him to handle alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he said - if not to find a solution - at least to make it share the responsibility for the situation ?
After six months of negotiations, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarity would be able to participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarity) never for a moment imagined they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they couldn't imagine that they would be driven out of power.
However, that's what happened.
In retrospect, it's astonishing that there could have been doubts.
Solidarity launched its campaign boldly.
A famous poster was hijacked for the occasion, that of a great classic of the western, The Train Will Be Hitting Three Times, had a great success: one sees a Gary Cooper with a ballot paper in hand instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
On June 4, it was the day of judgment.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was about to give birth to summer, the Polish communists were sent to the slaughterhouse by the voters.
For their final day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one last perversity that turned into an involuntary self-humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to cross out the names of those they did not want – in effect, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere one looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for, revenge for December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarity and put its leaders in prison.
The revolution with a pen !
Wielded with style, the pen that ultimately prevails over the sword, becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters ripped up their ballot sheet outright, thus decapitating the old regime with a swift blow.
Others savored the moment, perhaps pulling on a cigarette while blocking names on the ballots.
"He locked up my cousin", Pfft!, "Look at this apparatchik getting rich off our shortage", Pfft !
A dismissive expression, often equivalent to "Pfft" can be translated to "Oh please" or "Really?"
On the other hand, the communist campaign passed almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government-backed candidates took the trouble to put up posters.
Most relied on the monopoly they had in the media to get their message across: "Vote Lezek, a good communist".
One can say to his credit that the regime has acknowledged its defeat with remarkable dignity.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the party's main officials to declare to them: "Our defeat is total," we must find a political solution".
This meant that he did not want either violence or tampering, and the communists would have to live with the result of the vote.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarity was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of Eastern bloc.
The poll in Poland was extremely encouraging for anti-communists everywhere in the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days before suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began to tear down the fences erected along the border with Austria – a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "common European house" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
However, when the wall fell, politicians and experts universally acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming".
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom burst forth.
